<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Age:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> 30-ish<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Race:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Human<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Alignment</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Chaotic neutral<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Home City</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Kelethin<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Class:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Bard<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  -Brief History-</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
When Rhysling was but a babe, his family migrated from Qeynos to Highpass. Beset by unknown forces, the caravan was utterly destroyed, save himself and one other child. <br>
By the time he was found by a group of travelling wood elf rangers and druids, the other child had disappeared, and he was nearly dead of exposure. As one ranger was about to dispatch the ugly creature to put him out of his misery, the druid became unnerved by the unwavering gaze from the waif, and halted the execution. After a brief discussion it was decided to bring the child to Kelethin; there he would be judged and his fate decided by Tunare.<br>
Rhysling was fortunately spared, and raised atop Kelethin by the entire community. This was not generosity of spirit; it was the only way to resolve the elven sense of responsibility without burdening any family with the stain of human association.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Religion:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Raised as he was, Rhysling views everything with irreverence. No belief, however dearly held, is above analysis and ridicule. He leans toward Bristlebane as his deity of choice, since Bristlebane most closely mirrors his own world view.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Personality:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Rhysling is a loner. It's not a distrust or distaste for others, but simple self-reliance born of his elven upbringing. He needs no one else, and is therefore as comfortable alone as in company. His songs he sings for his own entertainment; if they also move others, he's appreciative, but indifferent. He left Kelethin upon achieving manhood and joining the Bardic guild, seeking to find knowledge of the events surrounding his family's death. Though he lost one eye in a boyhood accident (a prank gone awry,) the other retains the keen intensity that so unnerved the druid who was his benefactor.<br>
Having traveled the worlds, he's found that all Great Causes are often greater in the mind than in reality. As a result, Rhysling developed a mercenary attitude, with his loyalty belonging to his companions in battle, rather than to the cause for which he is paid to fight.<br>
<br>
One word to describe Rhysling:<br>
individual<br>
